Secs. 22-1—22-30. - Reserved. 
ARTICLE II. - OCCUPATION TAXES AND REGULATORY FEES[2] 

Footnotes: 
--- (2) --- 
State Law reference— Flea market vendors' records, O.C.G.A. § 10-1-360; Uniform Deceptive Trade Practices Act, O.C.G.A. § 10-1-370 et seq.; Fair Business Practices Act of 1975, O.C.G.A. § 10-1-390 et seq.; electrical contractors, plumbers, conditioned air contractors, low-voltage contractors, and utility contractors, O.C.G.A. § 43-14-1 et seq.; registration of nonresident contractors with state, O.C.G.A. § 48-13-31; . 

Sec. 22-31. - Enactment of ordinance. 
Pursuant to the authority provided in O.C.G.A. §§ 48-13-8 and 48-13-9, there is enacted a business license and regulatory fee ordinance for the unincorporated areas of the county. 
(Ord. of 5-14-2002, § 1) 
Sec. 22-32. - Administrator. 
The county building inspector shall be the administrator for the licensing of businesses under this article and the collection of fees imposed under this article and may be assisted by employees of the office of the building inspector. 
(Ord. of 5-14-2002, § 2) 
Cross reference— Administration, ch. 2. 
Sec. 22-33. - Imposition of regulatory fee. 
There is imposed an annual regulatory fee in the amount of $25.00 for the issuance of each business license issued pursuant to this article to cover the cost of inspection or investigation of such businesses, professions and occupations and as an aid in the regulation of such businesses, professions and occupations. The fee imposed by this article is imposed pursuant to the authority cited in section 22-31 and pursuant to the police powers of the county, and shall be paid within the time specified in this article. 
(Ord. of 5-14-2002, § 4) 
Sec. 22-34. - License required. 
(a)  None of the following businesses or practitioners of the following professions or occupations shall do business in the unincorporated areas of the county (whether or not such person, firm or corporation has a location in the unincorporated areas of the county) without first obtaining a license to do so from the county building inspector's office: 
(1)  Building and construction contractors, subcontractors, and workers; 
(2)  Carnivals; 
(3)  Taxicab and limousine operators; 
(4)  Tattoo artists; 
(5)  Stables; 
(6)  Shooting galleries and firearm ranges; 
(7)  Scrap metal processors; 
(8)  Pawnbrokers; 
(9)  Food service establishments; 
(10)  Dealers in precious metals; 
(11)  Firearms dealers; 
(12)  Peddlers; 
(13)  Parking lots; 
(14)  Nursing and personal care homes; 
(15)  Newspaper vending boxes; 
(16)  Modeling agencies; 
(17)  Massage parlors; 
(18)  Landfills; 
(19)  Auto and motorcycle racing; 
(20)  Boardinghouses; 
(21)  Businesses that provide appearance bonds; 
(22)  Boxing and wrestling promoters; 
(23)  Hotels and motels; 
(24)  Hypnotists; 
(25)  Handwriting analysts; 
(26)  Health clubs, gyms, and spas; 
(27)  Fortunetellers; 
(28)  Garbage collectors; 
(29)  Escort services; 
(30)  Burglar and fire alarm installers; 
(31)  Locksmiths; 
(32)  Clubs or other businesses which rent or which charge admission for rooms, space or locations at which alcoholic beverages are consumed, whether such alcoholic beverages are sold by the business or brought to the premises by such business patrons; 
(33)  Pool halls; and 
(34)  Installers of modular, manufactured or mobile homes. 
(b)  The business license shall be issued by the county building inspector upon the completion of the application therefor and the payment of the fee hereinafter specified, provided however that no license shall be validly issued to any applicant whose place of business, if any, is not in full compliance with all minimum standard codes, nor to any applicant who is not in compliance with all applicable county ordinances, and the zoning rules and regulations adopted by Mitchell County, nor to any applicant who is not in compliance with all applicable statutes, codes and rules of the State of Georgia. 
(c)  The obtaining of a business license as provided in this article is made a condition precedent to doing business, engaging in, or the practice of, any such business, profession or occupation specified in subsection (a) of this section in the unincorporated areas of the county, whether or not the business or practitioner of such occupation or profession has a location in the unincorporated area of the county. The doing business, engaging in, or practice of, any business, profession or occupation not specified in subsection (a) of this section does not require the obtaining of the business license or the payment of the regulatory fee under this article. 
(d)  Each business or practitioner of any of the professions or occupations specified in subsection (a) of this section doing business in the unincorporated areas of the county (whether or not such business or practitioner has a location in the unincorporated area of the county) shall obtain a business license and pay the regulatory fee provided in this article prior to doing business in the unincorporated areas of the county, and may renew existing licenses on an annual basis. All regulatory fees for such renewals shall become due and payable on January 1 of each year, but no penalty shall be applied to such renewal licenses unless the regulatory fee shall not have been paid within 30 days from the due date. Failure to pay the regulatory fee and renew the business license within such 30 days each year shall be a violation of this article and shall subject the offender to the penalties set forth in section 22-38. Business licenses issued pursuant to this article are valid for the remainder of the calendar year in which the license was issued. 
(Ord. of 5-14-2002, §§ 3, 5, 6; Ord. No. 2002-008, 10-8-2002) 
Sec. 22-35. - Display; transferability of license. 
Business licenses issued under this article shall be conspicuously displayed at the business location. No licenses issued under this article shall be transferable from one owner to a subsequent owner of the same business. 
(Ord. of 5-14-2002, § 7) 
Sec. 22-36. - Additional license, regulatory fee required. 
The business license shall authorize the holder of a license issued under this article to do business in the unincorporated areas of the county in one of the businesses, occupations or professions listed in section 22-34(a). For each additional line of business or occupation or profession specified in section 22-34(a) in which the business or practitioner does business in the unincorporated area of the county, the license holder will be required to obtain an additional license and pay an additional regulatory fee. 
(Ord. of 5-14-2002, § 8) 
Sec. 22-37. - Business hours of business establishments serving alcoholic beverages. 
No business establishment that allows consumption of alcoholic beverages on premises shall remain open between the hours of 12:30 a.m. and 6:00 a.m., Monday through Friday. No business establishment that allows consumption of alcoholic beverages on premises shall remain open between the hours of 2:00 a.m. and 6:00 a.m. on Saturday. No person, except the owner, operator or his employee, shall be or remain on the premises of such business establishment during the hours when it is required to be closed. The business license of any person or firm which holds an alcoholic beverage license which authorizes the consumption of alcohol on the premises shall be suspended for a period of six months upon the action of the board of commissioners to continue the suspension of such alcoholic beverage license following the suspension of such license by the chairman of the board of commissioners, or to suspend or revoke such license, which six-month period shall commence to run upon the taking of such action by the board of commissioners regarding the alcoholic beverage license, and the holder of the business license shall surrender same to the building inspector within five days of its suspension. 
(Ord. of 5-14-2002, § 9) 
Sec. 22-38. - Violations. 
(a)  The magistrate court of the county shall have jurisdiction over and hear cases brought for violations of this article. 
(b)  Any person violating the provisions of this article shall, upon conviction before the magistrate court of the county, be fined in an amount not to exceed $500.00 or imprisoned for a period not exceeding 90 days, or both. 
(c)  Each day of doing business in violation of this article shall be considered a separate offense. 
(d)  The building inspector and his designees and all law enforcement officers of the county are authorized to issue summons and citations for violations of this article. 
(Ord. of 5-14-2002, § 10) 
Sec. 22-39. - Invalidity of article. 
If any section, provision, or clause of any part of this article shall be declared invalid or unconstitutional, or if the provisions of any part of this article as applied to any particular situation or set of circumstances shall be declared invalid or unconstitutional, such invalidity shall not be construed to affect the portions of this article not so held to be invalid. 
(Ord. of 5-14-2002, § 11) 
Sec. 22-40. - Exempt businesses, practitioners. 
Nothing contained in this article shall be construed to require the obtaining of the business license required under this article, or the payment of the regulatory fee set forth in this article by: 
(1)  Any business or practitioner of the professions or occupations listed in O.C.G.A. § 48-13-9(c); 
(2)  Any business or practitioner whose office is maintained by and who is employed by, in practice or occupation, exclusively by the United States, the state, a municipality or county of the state, instrumentalities of the United States, the state, or a municipality or county of the state; or 
(3)  Any business or practitioner of a profession or occupation not listed in section 22-34(a). 
(Ord. of 5-14-2002, § 12)
